<TITLE> Bird flu infests Dhaka poultry, 95,000 fowls culled </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 17 (bdnews24.com)Livestock officials have culled 95,000 fowls at a poultry farm in the capital after detection of avian influenza there, an official said Sunday. Efforts are underway to cull another 60,000 birds, Sheikh Saidur Rahman, district livestock officer, told bdnews24.com. The culling of the fowlsinfected or feared to be infectedat Omega Poultry Farm in Uttar Badda started Saturday evening after livestock officials had detected the strain of fatal bird flu virus H5N1 among the birds. "Two more pits are being dug at the site for burying the culled birds, chicken feeds and waste," Saidur Rahman told bdnews24.com. Ataur Rahman Nayan, an Omega staffer, said the farm authorities had informed the government office of the incidence of disease Saturday. There are some 1.5 lakh fowls in the farm, Nayan said. He said he was not aware of how the virus infected the fowls, despite all precautions taken by the farm to keep the disease at bay. Earlier, Sunil Chandra Ghosh, director general of the livestock directorate, had told bdnews24.com, "The authorities will take necessary steps to stop the spread of the disease from that farm. All chicken feed and waste generated at the farm have been also buried for the purpose." Alees Ahmed Khan, owner of the farm, said he lost about Tk 12 crore so far to the incidence of the disease. "The government is paying only Tk 60 for every culled fowl which doesn't compensate for the huge losses at all," Khan said. bdnews24.
